    {
        "content": "<p>We have <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Set.Bounded#doc\">docs#Set.Bounded</a>, <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=BddAbove#doc\">docs#BddAbove</a>, and <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=BddBelow#doc\">docs#BddBelow</a>. Should we reuse the former for the other two?</p>",
        "id": 391579523,
        "sender_full_name": "Yury G. Kudryashov",
        "timestamp": 1694988401
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>No. <span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"459227\">Violeta Hernández</span> added (a lot of API for) the former because she didn't know about the latter two, but in general we prefer predicates specialised to <code>&lt;=</code>, <code>&gt;=</code> for usability.</p>",
        "id": 391621355,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1695014237
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Should we drop the former then?</p>",
        "id": 391715370,
        "sender_full_name": "Yury G. Kudryashov",
        "timestamp": 1695048103
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Or at least mention <code>BddAbove</code>/<code>BddBelow</code> in the docstring?</p>",
        "id": 391715538,
        "sender_full_name": "Yury G. Kudryashov",
        "timestamp": 1695048145
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>What are the current uses of <code>Set.Bounded</code>? In principle, I'm happy to drop it.</p>",
        "id": 391715705,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1695048193
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It is used in <code>Order/Bounded</code> (a lot), in <code>Order/RelClasses</code> (def + 2 lemmas), <code>Order/WellFounded</code> (2 lemmas), <code>Cardinal/Cofinality</code> (2 theorems), and <code>Ordinal/Arithmetic</code> (once).</p>",
        "id": 391801427,
        "sender_full_name": "Yury G. Kudryashov",
        "timestamp": 1695085155
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Do you know that Lean 4 extension can show all uses of a definition/lemma?</p>",
